subject: Add support for log-handler
commitMessage:
Add support for log-handler

This handler is based off of version handler with major differences in
handler_builder

Tested:
created the blackbox blob successfully using this lib.
Read the data from the blob using a host side tool

Signed-off-by: Gaurav Gandhi <gauravgandhi@google.com>

This seems like it'd throw everytime the blob name does not begin with /log/

Shouldn't we just be continuing instead of throwing?
throwing error inside for loop will also do the same job right?, this way if there is a typo in json file that could be caught in the logs right?

My memory of phosphor-ipmi-flash are a bit fuzzy..but aren't things besides log blobs being passed into this?

That is your main calls LogHandlersBuilder().buildHandlerConfigFromDefaultPaths() .. see here
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-ipmi-flash/+/48302/11/bmc/log-handler/main.cpp#24

which seems to iterate over the defaultPaths and lift all the jsons from that path here

https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-ipmi-flash/blob/a3f65698000d366b57d2916eae67518f89c1298b/bmc/buildjson.hpp#L49

and
https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-ipmi-flash/blob/a3f65698000d366b57d2916eae67518f89c1298b/bmc/buildjson.hpp#L61


default paths defined here

https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-ipmi-flash/blob/a3f65698000d366b57d2916eae67518f89c1298b/bmc/buildjson.cpp#L71

ultimately the json object gets passed to this handler
https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-ipmi-flash/blob/a3f65698000d366b57d2916eae67518f89c1298b/bmc/buildjson.hpp#L84


So it seems like all the jsons in the system would get parsed and it's not an error condition for a json to omit a log blob.

So throwing an error, catching it and then printing something out would spam the journal.

this seems to allow you to deeply test a lot more scenarios.
e.g

- what happens when the systemd service fails? Does the open/stat/whatever work correctly?
- what happens when open can't actually open the file or if it's an empty file
- what happens when the file is HUGE? Should we refuse to read files that are bigger than XXMB?
- if we open a file with a given session number and read the data but open the file again with a different session number and the data refreshes is the first session properly kept up to date?
More code coverage will be added in a follow up review
